ce:section.ce:para:
Carrot (Daucus carota L.) is an important root vegetable, and consists of several rich bioactive compounds such as carbohydrates, carotenoids, polyphenols and dietary fibres [46]. Therefore, carrot was selected as a carbon source for the synthesis of CDs by single-step hydrothermal method. The fabrication of CDs involves carbonization of above chemical compounds via hydrolysis, dehydration and decomposition, resulting to form fluorescent carbon dots. As a result, the color of crude carbonized carrot solution becomes dark brown, however the solution color was changed to light yellow after dialysis and shown blue color emission when irradiated under UV light at 365 nm, suggesting the formation of CDs (Scheme 1
                        ). Fig. 1
                        a shows the absorbance spectrum of CDs and the maximum absorbances were observed at 330, 345 and 365 nm, indicating n-π and π-π electronic transitions in the CDs because of carbonyl and conjugated CC system. Subsequently, when excited as-synthesized CDs at 381 nm, emission peak was observed at 455 nm, emitting blue color fluorescence when irradiated the solution by UV light at 365 nm (Inset of Fig. 1a). The fluorescent CDs synthesized using carrot as carbon source exhibit excitation and emission peaks at 381 and 455 nm, respectively (Fig. 1a). We also studied the excitation-wavelength dependent fluorescence behavior of CDs at different excitation wavelength from 300 to 520 nm (Fig. 1b). It can be observed that the fluorescence emission intensity increases with increase of excitation wavelength up to 380 nm, thereafter decreasing the emission intensity with red-shifts, suggesting the formation of CDs with different sizes and with multifunctional organic groups on the surfaces of CDs. The fluorescence quantum yield of the as-synthesized CDs was 7.60%, which is measured by quinine sulfate as reference.
